{{for|the Chicago anarchist newspaper|Arbeiter-Zeitung (Chicago)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}} {{Infobox newspaper | name = Arbeiter-Zeitung | logo = | image = File:Arbeiter-Zeitung.png | caption = The front page of the ''Arbeiter-Zeitung'', 14 April 1910. | type = Daily newspaper | format = | owners = | founder = | publisher = | editor = | chiefeditor = | assoceditor = | maneditor = | newseditor = | managingeditordesign = | campuseditor = | campuschief = | opeditor = | sportseditor = | photoeditor = | staff = | foundation = 12 July 1889 | political = Social democrat | language = [[German language|German]] | ceased publication = 1991 | headquarters = | circulation = | sister newspapers = | ISSN = | oclc = | website = }}
'''Arbeiter Zeitung''' (meaning “Workers’ Newspaper” in English) was the daily of the [[Social Democratic Party of Austria|Social Democrat Party]] and published in Austria. It existed between 1889 and 1991.
==History and profile== ''Arbeiter Zeitung'' was started on 12 July 1889 by the Socialist Party<ref>{{cite web|title=Austria Press|url=http://www.pressreference.com/A-Be/Austria.html|work=Press Reference|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> and [[Victor Adler]]. The paper was banned in 1934 after the 13 February issue, but reappeared on 4 August 1945 as the main organ of the Austrian Social Democrat Party, continuing until 1989, providing general coverage of Austrian and international news. From 1985 through 1989 it was published under the title '''''Neue AZ'''''; from 1989 to 1991 it was published as '''''AZ'''''.<ref>Library of Congress Catalog</ref> From 1989 until 1991 it was published as an independent newspaper, and ceased publication in 1991.<ref>"The Feuilleton of the Viennese Arbeiter-Zeitung 1918-1934: Production Parameters and Personality Problems" Deborah Holmes, ''Austrian Studies,'' '''14''' (1), 1 October 2006, pp. 99-117 [http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/mhra/aus/2006/00000014/00000001/art00005 abstract]</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1=Mary Kelly|editor2=Gianpietro Mazzoleni|editor3=Denis McQuail|title=The Media in Europe: The Euromedia Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HYCVxSFNNpkC&pg=PA5|date=31 January 2004|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-4131-6|page=5}}</ref>
In the 1920s the circulation of the daily reached 100,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austria Press|url=http://www.pressreference.com/A-Be/Austria.html|work=Press Reference|accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref> The paper reduced its circulation by one quarter from 1960 to 1990.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Jens Lucht|author2=Linards Udris|title=Transformation of media structures and media content. A diachronic analysis of five Western European countries|journal=NCCR Democracy|date=October 2010|series=Working Paper No. 49|url=http://www.nccr-democracy.uzh.ch/publications/workingpaper/pdf/WP_49.pdf|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>
Among its noted contributors and editors in the pre-war period was its cultural editor [[David Josef Bach]].<ref>"David Josef Bach and Christian Glanz, (1 October 2006). [http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/mhra/aus/2006/00000014/00000001/art00009 Viennese Debates on Modern Music] ''Austrian Studies,'' '''14''' (1), pp. 185-195</ref> [[Ernst Fischer (writer)|Ernst Fischer]] served as the editor of the paper.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Oliver Rathkolb|author2=Otmar Binder|title=The Paradoxical Republic: Austria 1945-2005|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1jCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA140|accessdate=18 April 2015|date=15 January 2010|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=978-1-78238-396-3|page=140}}</ref>
