The '''Constitution (Amendment No. 24) Act, 1936''' ([[Act of parliament|Act]] no. 18 of 1936; previously [[bill (law)|Bill]] no. 20 of 1934) was an act of the [[Oireachtas (Irish Free State)|Oireachtas]] (parliament) of the [[Irish Free State]] which abolished [[Seanad Éireann (Irish Free State)|Seanad Éireann]], the [[upper house]] of the Oireachtas, which thenceforth was [[unicameral]], with [[Dáil Éireann (Irish Free State)|Dáil Éireann]] as the sole house. The bill was introduced in 1934 by [[Government of the 8th Dáil|the Fianna Fáil government]] of [[Éamon de Valera]], which was frustrated by the Seanad's repeated use of its power to delay (though not veto) legislation. In particular, [[Fianna Fáil]] favoured eliminating [[Monarchy in the Irish Free State|symbols of monarchy]] from the Free State, which the Seanad, with more [[Southern Irish unionism|Southern Unionist]] members, feared would [[Ireland–United Kingdom relations|antagonise the United Kingdom]].
The Seanad opposed the bill, declining in June 1934 to give it a [[second reading]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Constitution (Amendment No. 24) Bill, 1934 — Second Stage (Resumed). |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/1934-06-01/2/ |website=Seanad Éireann debate |accessdate=4 October 2018 |language=en-ie |date=1 June 1934}}</ref> The Dáil resubmitted the bill in December 1935<ref>{{cite web |title=Constitution (Amendment No. 24) Bill, 1934 — Motion Under Article 38A of the Constitution |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1935-12-12/31/ |website=Dáil Éireann debate |language=en-ie |date=12 December 1935}}</ref> and the Seanad passed a motion declining to pass it unless a replacement second chamber was created.<ref>{{cite web |title=Constitution (Amendment No. 24) Bill, 1935 — Motion by Senator Douglas (Resumed) |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/1936-01-16/4/ |website=Seanad Éireann debate |language=en-ie |date=16 January 1936}}</ref> In May 1936, the Dáil overrode the Seanad's refusal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Constitution (Amendment No. 24) Bill, 1934 — Motion of Enactment. |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1936-05-28/9/ |website=Dáil Éireann debate |accessdate=4 October 2018 |language=en-ie |date=28 May 1936}}</ref>
The act deleted 16 articles of the [[Constitution of the Irish Free State|1922 Constitution]] and made consequential amendments to numerous others. It also increased from the threshold for passing a [[Resolution (law)|resolution]] of [[impeachment]] (of [[Judiciary of the Republic of Ireland|judges]] or the [[Comptroller and Auditor General of Ireland|Comptroller and Auditor General]]) from a simple [[majority]] to a four-sevenths [[supermajority]], since only one house, rather than two, would thenceforth be voting on such a resolution.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.lawlibrary.ie/rss/barreview/3-2013.pdf |publisher=Law Library |location=Dublin |format=PDF |journal=Bar Review |date=June 2013 |title=The Proposed Abolition of the Seanad and the Implications for Judicial Independence |first=Bláthna |last=Ruane}}</ref>
When [[Seanad Éireann|a new Seanad]] was created by the [[Constitution of Ireland|1937 Constitution]] it was in a weakened form with measures to ensure a likely government majority (such as allowing 11 senators to be [[nominated by the Taoiseach]] of the day). A [[Thirty-second Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2013|2013 attempt to abolish the Seanad]] was rejected by referendum. The 1936 act was formally repealed as [[spent law|spent]] by the [[Statute Law Revision Act 2016]].
==References== ===Sources=== * {{cite web |title=Constitution (Amendment No. 24) Act, 1936 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1936/act/18/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book |accessdate=4 October 2018 |language=en}} * {{cite web |title=Constitution (Amendment No. 24) Act, 1936 : Dáil debates |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/bills/bill/1934/20/?tab=debates |website=Bills and Acts |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=4 October 2018 |language=en-ie |date=22 March 1934}}
