{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox film | name = Golden Horseshoes | image = | caption = | director = [[Nouri Bouzid]] | producer = [[Ahmed Baha Attia]] | writer = Nouri Bouzid | starring = [[Hichem Rostom]] | music = | cinematography = Youssef Ben Youssef | editing = Kahéna Attia | distributor = | released = {{film date|1989}} | runtime = 104 minutes | country = Tunisia | language = Arabic | budget = }}
'''''Golden Horseshoes''''' ({{lang-ar|صفايح ذهب}}, [[Transliteration|translit.]]&nbsp;Safa'ih min dhahab, {{lang-fr|Les Sabots en or}}) is a 1989 Tunisian [[drama film]] directed by [[Nouri Bouzid]]. It was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name="festival-cannes.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/260/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Golden Horseshoes |accessdate=2 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>
==Plot== Youssef Soltane, a 45-year-old Tunisian intellectual, is the product of a generation that lived the era of euphoria and great ideologies in the sixties, and their subsequent failure. He was incarcerated and tortured for his political opinions. Furthermore, his relationship with Zineb, a young, beautiful bourgeois, only brings him more trouble. During one long winter night, Youssef wanders in search of an emotional haven, prey to all the questions that flood his memory.
