{{short description|A series of 28 small underwater volcanoes on the Chatham Rise, east of New Zealand}} [[File:Di-8954-niwa.jpg|thumbnail|Graveyard Knolls]] {{Infobox Seamount | Name = Graveyard Seamounts | Depth = {{convert|750|to|1000|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="ocea-spot"/> | Height = {{convert|100|to|400|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="ocea-spot"/> | Map = | Map caption = | Photo = | Photo alt = | Photo caption = | Photo size = | Summit area = {{convert|140|km2|mi2|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="ocea-spot"/> | Translation = | Language = | Pronunciation = | Location = [[Chatham Rise]], east of [[New Zealand]]<ref name="ocea-spot"/> | Group = | Coordinates = {{coord|42|45|S|180|0|W|display=inline, title}} | Country = [[New Zealand]] | Type = | Volcanic group = | Range = | Age = [[Cenozoic|Late Cenozoic]] | Last activity = | Last eruption = | Discovered = | Discovered by = | First visit = }}
The '''Graveyard Seamounts''' is the informal name for the Graveyard Knolls<ref>[http://www.linz.govt.nz/regulatory/place-names/recent-place-name-decisions-and-place-names-interest/nzgb-decisions-may-2015 New Zealand Geographic Board, May 2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216063416/http://www.linz.govt.nz/regulatory/place-names/recent-place-name-decisions-and-place-names-interest/nzgb-decisions-may-2015 |date=2016-02-16 }}</ref> These are a series of 28 small [[seamount]]s ([[Submarine volcano|underwater volcano]]es) and edifices located on the [[Chatham Rise]], east of [[New Zealand]]. They cover about {{convert|140|km2|mi2|0|abbr=on}} and stand out from the surrounding oceanic plateau that measures several hundred kilometers. They are named after various morose figures following the naming of the largest of the knolls as "the Graveyard" as it was a graveyard of fishing gear that became stuck on it. The most prominent among the group of knolls are Ghoul, Diabolical, Voodoo, Scroll, Hartless, Pyre, Gothic, Zombie, Mummy, Headstone, Morgue and Graveyard (ordered roughly by increasing size).<ref name="ocea-spot"/>
== Geography and geology == While the official name for these features refers to [[Hillock|knolls]],<ref name="IHO 2008">IHO, 2008. Standardization of Undersea Feature Names: Guidelines Proposal form Terminology, 4th ed. International Hydrographic Organisation and Intergovernmental Oceanographic Commission, Monaco.</ref> researchers in different disciplines see these features in different terms. These features are often referred to as seamounts where a seamount is described as any geographic isolated topographic feature on the seafloor taller than {{convert|100|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}, including ones whose summit regions may temporarily emerge above sea level, but not including features that are located on continental shelves or that are part of other major landmasses.<ref>{{cite journal|authors=Hubert Staudigel, Anthony A.P. Koppers, J. William Lavelle, Tony J. Pitcher, and Timothy M. Shank|title=Box 1: Defining the Word Seamounts|journal=[[Oceanography (journal)|Oceanography]]|url=http://tos.org/oceanography/article/defining-the-word-seamount|publisher=[[Oceanography Society]]}}</ref>
The seamounts are the site of volcanism from the late [[Cenozoic]] era. The knolls are {{convert|100|to|400|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} high, stand {{convert|1050|to|1200|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} deep at their base and {{convert|750|to|1000|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} at their summit. Many of the seamounts bear marks of [[tidal scour]] from [[erosion#Water|water erosion]], the result of millions of years of wear by a current moving at {{convert|1|to|2|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} per second.<ref name="ocea-spot">{{cite journal|authors=Malcolm R. Clark, Ashley A. Rowden, Ian Wright, Mirelle Consalvey|title=Spotlight 7: Graveyards Seamounts|journal=[[Oceanography (journal)|Oceanography]]|url=http://www.tos.org/oceanography/issues/issue_archive/issue_pdfs/23_1/23-1_clark1.pdf|accessdate=26 July 2010|publisher=[[Oceanography Society]]}}</ref>
== Ecology == The Graveyard Knolls is a home to over 50 species of fish, dominated by the [[orange roughy]] (''Hoplostethus atlanticus''), [[black oreo]] (''Allocyttus niger''), and [[cardinalfish]] ('''Apogonidae'''). Orange roughy in particular aggregate on the Graveyard Knolls for [[Spawn (biology)|spawning]] and their visits here have supported a commercial fishery since the mid-1990s. A number of the seamounts are also home to extensive [[deep water coral]] forests, made up of ''[[Caryophylliidae|Solenosmilia variabilis]]'' and ''[[Madrepora oculata]]'', both species not known to be of wide extent near New Zealand until camera surveys of Graveyard Knolls in 2001 revealed their extent. These forests offer a home to a diverse invertebrate community that includes [[squat lobster]]s, [[seastar]]s, [[brittlestar]]s, [[polychaete worm]]s, and [[crab]]s. In contrast, the knolls in the group that are affected by [[bottom trawling]] are mostly barren, with few coral and a completely different ecosystem.<ref name="ocea-spot"/>
In 2001, witnessing the damage of bottom trawling to seamount communities, 19 seamounts off the coast of New Zealand were closed off to bottom trawling, three of them from the Graveyard group. Timed surveys of the seamounts over the years are being used to examine how well a seamount coral community recovers from the effects of dredging over time.<ref name="ocea-spot"/>
