{{short description|12th-century illegitimate daughter of King Henry I of England}}
{{other people||Matilda FitzRoy (disambiguation){{!}}Matilda FitzRoy}}
'''Maud, Abbess of Montivilliers''' was a natural daughter of [[Henry I of England]] by an unknown [[Mistress (lover)|mistress]].<ref name=White>Geoffrey H. White, ‘ "Associates" and Illegitimate Children of King Henry (I) Beauclerc of England’, Appendix D of ''[[The Complete Peerage]]'', Volume XI, 1949.</ref><ref name=Thompson/> She is not to be confused with Isabel, another illegitimate daughter of Henry I by his mistress Isabel de Beaumont<ref name=White/><ref name=Thompson/> (c. 1102 – c. 1172), herself a sister of [[Robert de Beaumont, 2nd Earl of Leicester]].

Maud (or Mathilda) was a half-sister of the [[Empress Matilda]], who agreed to work with her.<ref name=Thompson>Kathleen Thompson, ‘Affairs of State: the illegitimate children of Henry I’, ''Journal of Medieval History'', 29 (2003), pp. 129–151.</ref> She may have valued her company and advice.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}} <!-- most probably from Chibnall, Empress Mathilda, p. 186? -->

Matilda became the [[abbess]] of the [[Montivilliers|Abbey Church of Notre-Dame, Montivilliers]], and for that reason is best known as Maud of Montivilliers.

