{{Infobox song contest country | Name = Moldova | Member station = | National selection event ={{Collapsible list | title = '''Internal Selection''' | 2016 }} | Apps = 0 | First = {{Tscyr|2017}} | Last = | Best = | Worst = | Website = | Current TSC = 2017 }}
The participation of '''Moldova in the Turkvision Song Contest''' was expected to begin in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]], at the [[Turkvision Song Contest 2016]]. The national broadcaster responsible for the selection process of Moldova's participants has yet to be known. Moldova had selected Polina Stefoglo with her song "Yallah Yallah!", as their debut entry. However, the 2016 contest was subsequently cancelled due to the [[December 2016 Istanbul bombings]].
==Origins of the contest== Turkvision is an annual song contest which was created by [[TÜRKSOY]] in cooperation with the Turkish music channel [[TMB TV]]. Based on the similar format of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], Turkvision focuses primarily on participating [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] countries and regions. The participating countries and regions have to take part in the Semi Final. A juror from each nation awards between 1 and 10 points for every entry, except their own. An amount of 12 to 15 nations qualify for the Grand Final where the jury determines the winner. TÜRKSOY has stated that televoting is going to be introduced in the future.<ref>{{cite web|title=What is Turkvision, How is the Format of Turkvision Song Contest|url=http://www.turkvision.info/What-is-Turkvision,-How-is-the-Format-of-Turkvision-Song-Contest-1-h.htm|publisher=turkvision.info|accessdate=22 April 2017|date=15 October 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308012519/http://turkvision.info/what-is-turkvision%2C-how-is-the-format-of-turkvision-song-contest-1-h.htm|archivedate=8 March 2016|df=}}</ref> Unlike the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] in which the winning country proceeds to host the following year's event, hosting of the Turkvision Song Contest takes place in the country or region that is also hosting the [[Culture and Arts Capital of the Turkic World|Turkish Capital of Culture]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Where Will Turkvision Be Held, In Which Country Is Turkvision|url=http://www.turkvision.info/Where-Will-Turkvision-Be-Held,-In-Which-Country-Is-Turkvision-4-h.htm|publisher=turkvision.info|accessdate=22 April 2017|date=15 October 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311020026/http://turkvision.info/where-will-turkvision-be-held%2C-in-which-country-is-turkvision-4-h.htm|archivedate=11 March 2016|df=}}</ref>
==History==
===Turkvision Song Contest 2016===
On 25 November 2016, it was announced that Moldova would be making their Turkvision debut at the [[Turkvision Song Contest 2016|2016 edition]], and had internally selected Polina Stefoglo, while her song was revealed to be sung in Turkish.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|url=https://eurovoix-world.com/moldova-polina-stefoglo-turkvision-2016/|title=Moldova: Polina Stefoglo To Turkvision 2016|date=25 November 2016|accessdate=25 November 2016|website=eurovoix-world.com|publisher=Eurovoix}}</ref> On 5 December 2016, Stefoglo's song was revealed to be called "Yallah Yallah!"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|url=https://eurovoix-world.com/moldova-yallah-yallah-title-first-turkvision-song-contest-entry/|title=Moldova: "Yallah Yallah!" Title of First Turkvision Song Contest Entry|date=5 December 2016|accessdate=5 May 2017|website=eurovoix-world.com|publisher=Eurovoix}}</ref> However, it was later confirmed that both of the 2016 contests had been cancelled due to the [[December 2016 Istanbul bombings]].
===Turkvision Song Contest 2017===
Following the cancellation of the [[Turkvision Song Contest 2016]], it was confirmed by the Ministry of Culture and Sports in Kazakhstan, that the 2017 edition would take place in [[Astana]], [[Kazakhstan]], and would coincide with other events taking place in the city as part of [[Expo 2017]].<ref name="TSC2017">{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|title=Turkvision Song Contest 2017 to be held in Kazakhstan|url=https://eurovoix-world.com/turkvision-song-contest-2017-to-be-held-in-kazakhstan/|website=eurovoix-world.com|publisher=Eurovoix|date=15 February 2017|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref> The contest was originally going to be held at the [[Barys Arena]],<ref name="Barys Arena">{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|title=Turkvision 17 Barys Arena announced as venue|url=https://eurovoix-world.com/turkvision17-barys-arena-announced-venue/|website=eurovoix-world.com|publisher=Eurovoix|date=16 February 2017|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref> with the two semi-finals taking place on 8 and 9 September, and the final on 10 September 2017.<ref name="Turkvision 2017">{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|title=Final of Turkvision 2017 to be held September 10|url=https://eurovoix-world.com/turkvision17-final-turkvision-2017-held-september-10/|website=eurovoix-world.com|publisher=Eurovoix|date=18 February 2017|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref> However, on 27 March 2017, it was announced that the dates and venue had subsequently been changed, with the [[Saryarka Velodrome]] as the new venue, and the contest itself taking place on 29 and 31 August 2017.<ref name="Velodrome">{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|title=Turkvision 17 venue and contest dates changed|url=https://eurovoix-world.com/turkvision17-venue-contest-dates-changed/|website=eurovoix-world.com|publisher=Eurovoix|date=27 March 2017|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>
