{{Infobox building | name = Sfatul Țării Palace | native_name = | former_names = | alternate_names = | image = Sfatul Țării Palace in Chișinău.jpg | alt = | caption = | map_type = | map_alt = | map_caption = | altitude = | building_type = | architectural_style = | structural_system = | cost = | ren_cost = | location = | address = 111 Alexei Mateevici | client = | owner = | current_tenants = | landlord = | coordinates = {{Coord|47|1|20|N|28|49|2|E|display=inline, title}} | start_date = 1902 | completion_date = | inauguration_date = 1905 | renovation_date = 1950s (architect [[Rosalia Spirer]]) | demolition_date = | destruction_date = | height = <!-- {{convert||m|ft}} --> | diameter = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = | floor_area = | main_contractor = | architect = Vladimir N. Țâganco | architecture_firm = | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | other_designers = | quantity_surveyor = | awards = | ren_architect = | ren_firm = | ren_str_engineer = | ren_serv_engineer = | ren_civ_engineer = | ren_oth_designers = | ren_qty_surveyor = | ren_awards = | url = | references = }}
The '''Sfatul Țării Palace''' is a [[building]] in [[Chișinău]], [[Moldova]].
== Overview == The building is located near [[Central Chișinău]]. It served as a meeting place for the [[Sfatul Țării]], the assembly which proclaimed the independence of the [[Moldavian Democratic Republic]] in 1917 then [[Union of Bessarabia with Romania|union]] with [[Romania]] in 1918. The building was heavily damaged in the Second World War. It is currently home to the [[Academy of Music, Theatre and Fine Arts]].
